    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-05-31T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-05-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="1093"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1093">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890D.01/6–145: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The British Prime Minister</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Churchill</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to President <persName type="to"
                            >Truman</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="84" xml:id="d1093fn84">Transmitted to the Acting Secretary of State by
                        the British Minister (Balfour) on June 1.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-05-31">May 31,
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>61. In the light of the deteriorating situation in the Levant States, His
                    Majesty’s Government felt bound to order the Commander-in-Chief of the Middle
                    East to intervene, in order to prevent further <pb facs="1136" n="1124"
                        xml:id="pg_1124"/> effusion of blood. My immediately following message<note
                        n="85" xml:id="d1093fn85">Copy not found in Department files.</note>
                    contains the statement on the subject which the Foreign Secretary has just made
                    in the House of Commons.<note n="86" xml:id="d1093fn86">
                        <hi rend="italic">Parliamentary Debates</hi>, House of Commons, 5th series,
                        vol. 411, col. 378.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Owing to the urgency, His Majesty’s Government felt they could not wait longer
                    for your reply to my message No. 59 but I feel sure that I may count on the
                    support of United States Government for the steps which we have felt bound to
                    take.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
